post_text:
Measles Case in Iowa

A case of measles has been reported in Iowa. This is the first case in our state since 2011 and is a good reminder to make sure that your family’s vaccines are up to date. The measles vaccine is highly effective (the patient with measles was not vaccinated) and all school-aged children should have two MMR doses by the time they start kindergarten.

If a case of measles is identified in our school, public health officials will require all unvaccinated students and staff to remain at home until 21 days after their last possible exposure to measles. Please make sure your family is protected. Vaccines save lives.

For more information on measles, please visit: https://idph.iowa.gov/cade/disease-information/measles or contact your local health department.

If you had conferences scheduled for this evening:

If you have students in grades PK-4: (West Side Early Childhood Center, John Cline Elementary, Carrie Lee Elementary)
Your child’s teacher will be contacting you to conference in a way that best meets the needs of your family. That may mean either setting time for a phone call or, if you prefer it, an alternative time to meet with your child’s teacher at school.

If you have students in grades 5-8: (Decorah Middle School)
Given your child’s conference is student-led, your conference can be set at a time convenient for you and your child’s Prime Time teacher. If there are other teachers you would like to meet with as well, please contact them too for a convenient time to meet.

If you have any questions regarding these plans, please feel free to contact building principals:
Rick Varney (382-3125)
Sarah Tobiason (382-3771)
Justin Albers (382-8427)

Thank you for your patience with the process!

post_text:
Due to the current gravel road conditions, we need to implement modified pick-up and drop-off locations for the safety of your sons and daughters. Bus drivers will assess the current gravel conditions as they drive their routes and will make calls as needed to families who are affected.

The pick-up and drop-off locations may be different from morning routes to afternoon routes depending on the ever-changing conditions of weather and the gravel roads.

We appreciate the teamwork and patience as we implement these changes for the safety of your children.

We have already made a few of these calls and have appreciated the cooperation from parents. We will implement this across all gravel bus routes beginning Friday morning March 2.

Thank you for working with the Decorah Community School District to ensure the safest possible situation for our students and drivers.

Thank you!

Please help us get the word out: We (Decorah Community School District) are NOT supporting, endorsing, nor have any affiliation with GroupRaise. The Decorah Police Department has been contacted and they will be adding something to their Facebook page alerting folks about this as well.

Our Decorah Community School District name has been used within this email message as well as Decorah PTA. We do NOT have a PTA, however we have a PTO.

Please help us spread the word to our community and local businesses which are being targeted.

I have attached a copy of the message. Each of the blacked out areas contained the name or email address of the business this message was targeting.

Thank you for helping us spread the word.

DCSD has received hundreds of JUNK messages from people inviting us to view a Google document. These messages are coming from all different accounts and appear to be a Phishing scam looking for account credentials. Please do not open these messages and delete them if they seem to be questionable or something you were not expecting. Some of the message are also coming from DCSD staff or student email accounts. Please be aware, these message were not actually sent by the staff or students in this case.

If you have clicked on the link and entered the requests for information, please change your account password immediately!

Once we know more, we will post something on the district website at http://www.decorah.k12.ia.us

Winneshiek County Sheriff's Office
January 3, 2017 at 7:03 AM ·

ROAD CONDITION ALERT: Due to last night's rain, the roadways continue to be in extremely poor condition. The gravels and county roadways are 100% ice covered. Please use extreme caution if traveling and try to stay put, if possible (especially if on a gravel or county roadway).

Update (11:30 AM): Bluffton Road will be closed for a few hours this afternoon while country road crews work on the ice covered hills. It will reopen when the county has completed their work.

Update (6:10 AM): We currently have multiple vehicles stranded in the ditches, including a sand truck. We are working hard to assist motorists and deal with this situation, but calls are coming in faster than we can respond to them. PLEASE STAY OFF THE ROADS IF AT ALL POSSIBLE!
